{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641735"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:31:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:31:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17900"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.14,0.55,0.05,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96647"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7001"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24735"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following neurons in the arcuate nucleus signals satiety?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sim1/MC4RN","NPY/AgRP","POMC/CART","ZdR/Agg3","GABA/Glutamate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus plays a crucial role in regulating appetite and energy balance. It contains two main populations of neurons that have opposing effects on food intake. \u003Cstrong\u003EPOMC/CART\u003C/strong\u003E neurons are responsible for signalling satiety and reducing food intake. They release peptides that activate melanocortin receptors, which are involved in the suppression of appetite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENPY/AgRP\u003C/strong\u003E neurons, on the other hand, promote feeding and increase appetite. They release neuropeptide Y and agouti-related peptide, which inhibit the activity of POMC/CART neurons and stimulate food intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESim1/MC4RN\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific neuron type in the arcuate nucleus but refers to a pathway involving melanocortin receptors, which are activated by POMC/CART neurons to reduce appetite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZdR/Agg3\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EGABA/Glutamate\u003C/strong\u003E are not specific neuron types related to satiety signalling in the arcuate nucleus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus contains neurons that regulate appetite and energy balance.","POMC/CART neurons in the arcuate nucleus signal satiety and reduce food intake.","NPY/AgRP neurons promote feeding and increase appetite."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 72; pg. 880","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020;64(4):607-47.","Austin J, Marks D. Hormonal regulators of appetite. Int J Pediatr Endocrinol. 2009;2009:141753.","Hernando-Redondo J, Toloba A, Benaiges D, Salas-Salvad\u00f3 J, Mart\u00ednez-Gonzalez MA, Corella D, et al. Mid- and long-term changes in satiety-related hormones, lipid and glucose metabolism, and inflammation after a Mediterranean diet intervention with the goal of losing weight: A randomized, clinical trial. Front Nutr. 2022;9:950900.","Yeung AY, Tadi P. Physiology, obesity neurohormonal appetite and satiety control. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 [updated 2023 Jan 3]."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96647"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:32:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","l